CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Treaty between the Republic of Texas and the United States re-affirmed that the boundary established by the treaty of 12 January 1828 between the United States and Mexico would be observed by the United States and the Republic of Texas.

The Republic of Texas officially established its boundaries: on the north and east, the Adams-Onis Treaty line; on the south the Rio Grande River; and on the west, from the source of the Rio Grande River north to the 42d parallel. Area between the Rio Grande and Nueces Rivers remained in dispute, and neither the Republic of Texas nor Mexico established effective control of the area.
CITATION: (Texas Repub. Laws 1836, 1st cong./p. 133; Frantz and Cox, 29, 31; Stephens and Holmes, 34)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Constitution of the Republic of Texas implicitly recognized the earlier Mexican municipalities as the Republic's original twenty-three counties.

NAME: Republic of Texas (non-county area)
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Texas declared its independence from Mexico; map depicts non-county area in the Republic of Texas.
CITATION: ("Republic of Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 5:537-538; Swindler, 9:247, 249)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Provisional Government of Texas was established by the Consultation, a group of delegates who met to discuss the war with Mexico and the movement toward Texas independence; the Provisional Government governed Texas until 1 March 1836.
Treaty between Mexico and the United States re-affirmed the boundary between the two countries as established by the Adams-Onis Treaty of 1819.

[December 1824] Department of Texas, also known as the District of Bexar, was organized as a subdivision of the state of Coahuila and Texas. Full boundaries and extent of Bexar not defined [not mapped].
CITATION: ("Coahuila and Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 2:171)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Under the 1824 Constitution for the Republic of Mexico, the state of Coahuila and the former Spanish province of Texas were united and organized as the state of Coahuila and Texas; included part of present east Texas and the northern part of Mexico.
CITATION: (Bacarisse, 345; "Coahuila and Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 2:171)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: New Mexico was declared a territory by the Mexican government; included western part of present Texas [not mapped].
Province of Texas became a separate political entity in Mexico.

NAME: Mexico
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Republic of Mexico gained its independence from Spain; present Texas became part of Mexico. Transfer of authority over Texas took place 24 August 1822.
CITATION: (Beers, 100; "Mexican War of Independence," New Handbook of Texas, 4:698)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Adams-Onis Treaty between the United States and Spain established the boundary between the two countries from the Gulf of Mexico to the Pacific Ocean. Ratifications exchanged 22 February 1821.

NAME: Spain
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Starting in 1726 the area in present Texas became a separate province of the Viceroyalty of New Spain.

[1689-1693] Governor of the Spanish province of Coahuila (part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain) extended his authority to include Texas. His authority ended with the withdrawal of the Spanish missions from east Texas in 1693.
CITATION: (Beers, 97; "Coahuila and Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 2:171)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: [1716] Coahuila Province again extended its authority over Texas.
CITATION: (Beers, 97-98; "Coahuila and Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 2:171)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Nuevo Santander created as a province in New Spain; included that part of present Texas between the Nueces and Rio Grande Rivers.
CITATION: ("Nuevo Santander," New Handbook of Texas, 4:1074-1075 and "Spanish Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 6:14)

CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 24 created from COMANCHE, anticipated creation of HAMILTON on 22 Jan 1858.

NAME: Non-County Area 25
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 25 created from MAVERICK.

NAME: ARCHER
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: ARCHER detached from JACK, attached to MONTAGUE "for judicial purposes."
CITATION: (Texas Laws 1870, 12th leg., called sess., ch. 40, sec. 13/p. 53)

NAME: ATASCOSA
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: FRIO detached from ATASCOSA, attached to MEDINA "for judicial purposes."
CITATION: (Texas Laws 1870, 12th leg., called sess., ch. 40, sec. 25/p. 57)

NAME: Non-County Area 26
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 26 created from EL PASO.

NAME: Non-County Area 3
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 3 created from MINA (now BASTROP).

NAME: Non-County Area 3
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 3 lost to FAYETTE.

NAME: Non-County Area 4
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 4 created from LAMAR.

NAME: Non-County Area 4
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 4 gained from LAMAR; attached to LAMAR for administrative and judicial purposes.

NAME: Non-County Area 5
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 5 created from MATAGORDA; anticipated creation of WHARTON on 3 Apr 1846.

NAME: Non-County Area 1
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 1 eliminated when it lost all territory to LIBERTY.

NAME: Non-County Area 6
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 6 created from VICTORIA; anticipated creation of CALHOUN on 4 April 1846.

NAME: Non-County Area 7
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 7 created from JACKSON.

NAME: Non-County Area 8
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 8 created from JACKSON.

NAME: Non-County Area 8
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 8 lost to creation of LAVACA, and lost to COLORADO.

NAME: Non-County Area 9
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 9 created from all that part of ROBERTSON north of LIMESTONE.

NAME: Cooke Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Cooke Land District re-organized, gained most of non-county area in Fannin Land District; implicitly ended the attachment of non-county areas in Fannin Land District to COLLIN and GRAYSON. Map depicts non-county area in Cooke Land District.

NAME: Denton Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Denton Land District re-organized, gained from Non-County Area 12, from Non-County Area 21 attached to HILL, and from non-county area in Fannin Land District. Denton Land District attached to HILL. Map depicts non-county area in Denton Land District.

NAME: Denton Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Parts of Denton Land District attached to PARKER and WISE lost to creation of Young Territory, and lost to YOUNG. The portion of Denton Land District attached to WISE became part of Young Territory, ending its attachment to WISE. Remainder of non-county area in Denton Land District remained attached to PARKER.

NAME: RED RIVER
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Survey of boundary between the Republic of Texas and the United States began. RED RIVER overlaps with LAFAYETTE (Ark.) and MILLER (Ark Terr., extinct) ended when Texas claims to the area were upheld.

NAME: Denton Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Denton Land District lost to creation of YOUNG; the part of Denton Land District northwest of YOUNG detached from PARKER, attached to WISE "for judicial purposes."

NAME: Fannin Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Parts of Fannin Land District attached to COLLIN and GRAYSON lost to creation of DENTON; unattached part of Fannin Land District lost to creation of HUNT.

NAME: Fannin Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Fannin Land District lost to creation of GRAYSON; northern part of Fannin Land District attached to GRAYSON for administrative and judicial purposes.

NAME: NACOGDOCHES
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Survey of boundary between the Republic of Texas and the United States began. NACOGDOCHES overlap with MILLER (Ark Terr., extinct) ended when Texas claims to the area were upheld.

NAME: Fannin Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Part of FANNIN reverted to non-county area that was designated Fannin Land District.

NAME: Fannin Land District
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Parts of Fannin Land District attached to COLLIN and GRAYSON lost to creation of COOKE.

NAME: Overlap Area 1
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Creation of COLLIN resulted in an overlap with GRAYSON.

NAME: Overlap Area 1
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Overlap Area 1 expanded when creation of DENTON resulted in an overlap with GRAYSON.

NAME: Overlap Area 2
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Creation of JACK resulted in an overlap with COOKE.

NAME: Overlap Area 3
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Creation of PALO PINTO resulted in an overlap with YOUNG.

NAME: Overlap Area 4
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Creation of CLAY resulted in an overlap area between CLAY and JACK. Dispute was settled in favor of JACK in March 1895.

NAME: Overlap Area 2
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Overlap Area 2, between COOKE and JACK, eliminated when CLAY created from COOKE.

NAME: Overlap Area 3
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Overlap Area 3 eliminated when PALO PINTO boundaries were clarified and YOUNG gained undisputed control of the area.

NAME: Overlap Area 4
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Overlap Area 4 eliminated when dispute between CLAY and JACK was settled in favor of JACK [see 24 Dec 1857].

NAME: Non-County Area 4
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 4 attached to LAMAR for administrative and judicial purposes.

NAME: Non-County Area 6
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 6 eliminated when it lost all territory to creation of CALHOUN.

NAME: Non-County Area 3
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Non-County Area 3 eliminated when it lost all territory to GONZALES.

NAME: Galveston Island
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Galveston Island did not fall under the jurisdiction of any county at the time Texas declared its independence from Mexico.
CITATION: ("Republic of Texas," New Handbook of Texas, 5:537-538; Swindler, 9:247, 249)

NAME: HARRISON
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Survey of boundary between the Republic of Texas and the United States began. HARRISON overlap with MILLER (Ark Terr., extinct) ended when Texas claims to the area were upheld.

NAME: GRAYSON
CREATION_OR_CHANGE: Creation of COLLIN resulted in an overlap with GRAYSON (see Overlap Area 1).
